	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Beef trade trends suggest EU farmers’ fears over Mercosur deal may be exaggerated</h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 August 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, Meat and Livestock Australia has reported that ‘EU beef imports during the nine months to March were down 13 per cent year-on-year to 139,654 tonnes swt’, but with a 23% increase in the average import price, raising it to US$9,265/tonne. EU beef import volumes ‘remained 51 per cent lower than 2006–07 when Brazilian supplies dominated the market’. An important factor behind this trend was held to be the restrictions in place since 2008 on the number of Brazilian farms eligible to export to the EU market, although exchange rate movements and soaring domestic demand in Brazil were also factors.</p><p>Scarce supplies from Argentina (shipments down by 32%) and Uruguay (shipments down by 24%) also contributed towards the rising trend in EU beef import prices. While imports from the US and Australia grew 57% and 13% respectively, this was from a very low base, with their combined exports to the EU in the last four months amounting to just over 18,000 tonnes.</p><p>This needs to be seen against the background of declining global beef production, with 2011 likely to see a ‘fourth consecutive year of global beef declines’. With supplies tight (Brazilian exports fell 9% in the season 2010–11), global beef prices are likely to stay at high levels for some time. The EU market now accounts for only 5% of Brazilian beef exports, behind Russia (33%), countries in the Middle East (collectively 42%) and exports to neighbouring Latin American countries.</p><p>Press reports meanwhile suggest that the EU–Mercosur FTA negotiations are in trouble. According to ICTSD, ‘the hopeful ambition that accompanied the May 2010 move to re-start negotiations … has wilted under the pressure of the EU’s growing debt problem, leaving officials on both sides wondering if the current economic climate makes reaching accord impossible.’ Brazilian representatives claim that within the negotiations, the rate of advance ‘has decelerated, there’s a serious risk of stagnation’.</p><p>Long-standing disagreements over liberalisation of agriculture are once again appearing. According to ICTSD, ‘Mercosur is again demanding that the EU cut large portions of their farm subsidies while Brussels continues to lobby for greater market access in manufactured products.’ EU negotiators, however, ‘are reluctant to lower either agriculture tariffs or subsidies …, given EU unemployment rates’. For their part, some Mercosur governments are facing elections, and the political temperature around the negotiations is rising. This has been compounded by high exchange rates in some Mercosur countries drawing in underpriced imports.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
