<i>TheBeefSite.com</i>, ‘Brazilian beef exports down in 2010-11’, 7 July 2011<br/>
<a href="http://www.thebeefsite.com/news/35138/brazilian-beef-exports-down-in-201011" target="_self">http://www.thebeefsite.com/news/35138/brazilian-beef-exports-down-in-201011</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Declining EU beef imports from Latin American suppliers, in a context of tight global markets, could bring windfall profits to ACP exporters, most noticeably Namibia. However, this will be critically influenced by exchange rate movements, with a strong rand currently increasing the attractiveness of neighbouring South African markets for both live cattle and beef cuts. This highlights the growing influence of exchange rate movements and relative prices to beef trade patterns. Whereas this was never previously an issue, given much higher EU beef prices, now as the gap between EU and world market prices has been closed, it has become a critical factor.</p><p>Looking forward, a critical issue in terms of trading into the EU market will be staying ahead of developments in food-safety, SPS- and production-process issues in the beef sector. This is likely to require considerable ongoing investment, with a constant eye kept on ensuring that the commercial returns gained warrant these ongoing investment commitments. Innovative marketing strategies are likely to prove critical in this regard.</p><p>As part of the 2013 round of CAP reforms, production standards for beef imported into the EU are likely to be tightened and more rigorously enforced to bring them into line with requirements placed on domestic EU beef producers (e.g. with regard to animal welfare requirements). Given the impact of the existing EU regulations on Brazilian beef exports to the EU, the stricter application of EU production standards to beef imports may well prove sufficient to discourage any major expansion of Brazilian beef exports to the EU, even if tariff concessions are granted as part of the EU–Mercosur trade agreement.</p><p>This raises the wider issue of how well placed ACP beef exporters will be to comply with any new EU production-process-related requirements in the cost-effective manner necessary to ensure the continued profitability of exporting to the EU.</p>
		</div>
		
